Privacy Policy for Accessing Public GitHub Repositories
Effective Date: 22 November 2024
This Privacy Policy explains how we collect, use, and disclose data when accessing public repositories on GitHub. By using our services, you agree to the terms outlined in this Privacy Policy.

1. Information We Collect
When accessing public GitHub repositories, we may collect:

Public Repository Data: This includes repository content, metadata (e.g., stars, forks), and contributor information made available through GitHub’s public API.
Usage Data: Non-personally identifiable information about your interaction with our services, such as API request logs and timestamps.
2. How We Use the Data
We use the data collected to:

Provide features and functionality for interacting with public GitHub repositories.
Analyze trends and improve our services.
Ensure compliance with GitHub’s Terms of Service and applicable laws.
3. Data Sharing and Disclosure
We do not sell or share collected data with third parties, except:

To comply with legal obligations or respond to lawful requests by public authorities.
To enforce our terms and policies.
4. Data Retention
We retain data only as long as necessary for the purposes outlined in this policy. Public repository data may be cached temporarily to improve performance.

5. Third-Party Services
This service uses GitHub’s public API to retrieve data. Your interaction with GitHub is governed by GitHub’s Privacy Statement.

6. User Rights
As we do not collect personal information from end users, rights under privacy laws such as GDPR or CCPA are generally not applicable. If you have concerns, please contact us.

7. Updates to This Privacy Policy
We may update this Privacy Policy from time to time. Changes will be posted on this page with the updated effective date.

8. Contact Us
If you have any questions or concerns about this Privacy Policy, please contact us at: [Your Contact Information]

